rows.title: Instructions
rows.content:
Please read these instructions aloud to your child

Next, you will see a treasure map of Skull Island with some locations on it.

After the story, you will take part in a little quiz about what you learned from the story.

You cannot submit your responses until after the story is finished.

rows.title: Quiz
rows.content:
We have some questions we'd like to ask you about the story. Please read these questions and possible answers aloud to your child and fill out the form based on their response.

Please be sure to scroll down to see all questions and answers

rows.label: How can you get to Skull Island?
rows.name: q02

rows.label: What did the dolphins play in?
rows.name: q03

rows.label: What was the sea lion doing?
rows.name: q08

rows.label: Why ask the animals for help?
rows.name: q12

rows.label: What was the treasure chest like to carry?
rows.name: q13

rows.label: Please select answer "Because it was fun."

The map was added to on different trips

options.label: For the animals to find it

rows.label: What is in the centre of the island?

rows.label: What do you need to follow to find the waterfall?

options.label: To stop the dolphins playing with it

rows.label: Why drag the rowing boat up the beach?

rows.title: Debrief
rows.content:
Thank you for participating in this online study, which explores whether engagement and narrative perspective work together to improve listening comprehension. Results of the study could inform future methods for improving narrative comprehension in children. We hope that you have found it interesting and have enjoyed the experience. However, if you have any concerns regarding the experience and you wish to speak to one of the researchers, please contact either:

  • Kerry Vart (Researcher)
    Email: bh56od@student.sunderland.ac.uk
  • Dr Glenn Williams (Research Supervisor)
    Email: glenn.williams@sunderland.ac.uk
    Phone: 0191 515 2522
You may feel you would like more advice and access to different stories to engage your child. The following websites offer access to free e-books and guidance on encouraging a love of books:
  • https://www.booktrust.org.uk/books-and-reading/tips-and-advice/reading-tips/
  • https://www.oxfordowl.co.uk/for-home/find-a-book/library-page/
If your child has enjoyed the pirate story you may wish to investigate further pirate activities on the websites below:
  • https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/topics/pirates
  • https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbbc/curations/pirates-on-cbbc

Thank you for taking the time to be a part of this study.

metadata.title: Perspective and Active Engagement Study
metadata.description:
This is a mouse tracking task where participants listen to a story while they view a map with several locations on it. 

Participants are randomly assigned to conditions where they are instructed that they will hear a second- or third-person perspective story about a character. They are also instructed that should actively click on locations mentioned within the story or to listen passively.

Participants can click on AOIs on the locations. X and Y axis locations, along with the label of the AOI is pushed to the data on the first click within an AOI. In the "Active" listening condition, a red X is drawn on the location on the first click.

Throughout the map section, the mouse coordinates are captured.

After this, participants complete a quiz, optionally submitting multiple choice answers assessing content from the story. A debrief follows this section.
